### Big data

- Volume. Amount of data generated and stored.
- Variety. Wide range of data sources and formats, structured, semi-structured(JSON) and unstructured(pdfs) and binary(images, audio, vidoe)
- Velocity. Speed data is generated and processed.
- Veracity. Accuracy and reliability of data.
- Variability. Consistency or inconsistency of the data in terms of format, quality and meaning.
- Value. How useful and relevant the data is.

Collecting data allows better business decisions. Predictive analysis can analyse historical data and predict future events or trends.

Business intelligence(BI) is the process of collecting, analysing and using the data to help make more informed business decisions.

### Data Maturity

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Reactive. Data is scattered all over, maybe in a bunch of excel spreadsheets. Spreadmarts suffer from data inconsistency, lack of governance, limited scalability, and inefficiency.
2. Informative. Centralize the data, making analysis and reporting easier. Mainly for rear view of what has already happened. Not very scalable and limited size and types of data.
3. Predictive. Moved over to the cloud which can handle larger quantities of data, different types, and data is ingested more frequently. Improved decision making, using advanced analytics/ML.
4. Transformative. Can handle any data. It's easy to onboard new data. It lets nontechnical end users to create reports and dashboards.

Want to move from IT having to build dashboards, to allowing customers to self serve and build them themselves.

Schema-on-write - data must conform to schema when written

Schema-on-read - data might be semi-structured one write, and only converted when read. e.g. maybe in a Data lake.

- Data storage
- Data processing
- Data access

- Relational data warehouse
- Data lake. Just storage no compute, but there are many compute engines that work with a data lake. e.g. Hadoop Distributed File System(HDFS). Can be hard to query or use the data in a lake.
- Modern data warehouse. Uses a lake for storage and ML, and data warehouse for normal querying.
- Data Fabric. A large fabric of systems that can ingest any sort of data.
- Data lakehouse. Gets rid of the relational data warehouse and just uses on repository a data lake. All data goes into the data lake, and all queries are done from the data lake. - Data Mesh. Data is kept within domains, and they are connected.

## Approaches to data modelling

#### Relational Modelling

Defining the relationship between tables.

A natural key is a key that already exists in a table.

Entity relationship(ER) diagrams, visualise the structure of the data base that represents entities(data) and relationships between them

A table is in it's first normal form(1NF) if

- Has a primary key.
- Each attribute in the table contains a single value, not a list of values. e.g. Name holds a single value.
- No repeating groups of columns. Shouldn't have Course1, Course2, etc. each course should have it's own row.

A table is in second normal form(2NF) if it also satisfies

- Every detail(non-key attribute) rely entirely on it's primary key and not any other detail. e.g. Course_Major just be determined solely by the StudentID not by the name or any other attribute in the table,  Nothing depends on half a key

A table is in third normal form(3NF) if it also

- Every non-key detail in the table should relate directly to the main key, not through another detail. e.g. Department head should not detpend on the major. Nothing depends on anything but the key.

Goal is for it to be in 3NF

Changes can be tracked by a history table, date, user, change, etc.

#### Dimensional Modelling

When querying of relational model becomes too slow or complex.

Facts. Data, values like sales or revenue.

Dimensions. Describe the data characteristics, like time, product, customer, location.

Dimensional modelling uses surrogate keys(artificial keys created automatically).

Some issues with natural keys, is they can be longer and more complex, contain sensitive information, potential duplication and non-standard formats.

To track changes you use slowly changing dimensions(SCDs).

Type 1. Overwrite data with new data and discard old data.

Type 2. Keep multiple version of the data.

Type 3. Create a new record for each change, so you can maintain a complete history of data.

Denormalisation. Where you include redundant copies of data in multiple tables. Means you don't need to join as many tables together. But redundant copeis of data must be kept in sync.

#### Common Data Model(CDM(

Standard structure for storing and organising data.

#### Data Vault

Hubs - business entities, like customers or products

Link - relationships between hubs, typically as a separate table. A link table contains a set of foreign keys that reference the primary keys of the related hubs.

Satellites - Store descriptive attributes about a hub or a link.

Complex

Data duplication, since data is stored at the atomic level.

Performance, can be slow and more complex queries.

Lack of standardisation.

## Main

Big data refers to large and complex datasets that are difficult to process and analyse using traditional data management tools

e.g. Financial data, healthcare data, public services data, social media data, website data

Number of rows could reach millions or billions.

Big data is data that is too big or too complex to be processed by traditional means. Usually tera or petabytes

Big five Vs of Big data

1. Volume
2. Variety of data(structured, unstructured, etc.)
3. Velocity: Speed the data is generated
4. Veracity: Degree the data can be trusted
5. Value: The business value of the data

Volume, relational databases were not designed to handle huge volumes of data

Larger data sets require longer processing times, which might not increase linearly so some algorithms can be too slow.

Variety

Most data is unstructured.  Relational databases can't handle unstructured data.

X gets structured data, user profiles, tweets, follower counts, semi structured hashtags, and unstructured, images, video

Velocity

Needs to increase speed of storage, processing and analysis is needed

Value

What can we do with it and what insights gained.

Veracity.

Trust in the data. Check might be needed.

Types

- Structured data, like in relational tables, not complex but could be voluminous
- Unstructured data is raw data, not arranged according to pre-set data model. e.g. images , video, invoices, emails
- Semi-structured data e.g. email, xml, json, noSQL, html

Healthcare, big data could predict disease outbreaks, personal treatment plans.

Business intelligence. Insights into customer behaviour, inventory control

Artificial intelligence and machine learning. They rely on large datasets to train algorithms and models.

Non-tabular data

Data that can't  be neatly organised into rows and columns. e.g. text, images, audio

80% of data is non-tabular and unstructured.

NLP

- Tokenisation: break text into words, phrases or tokens
- Stemming and lemmatisation: Reducing words to their root form or lemma to standardise different inflected variations of words.
- Part-of-speech tagging: Labelling each word with its part of speech(noun, verb, adjective, etc.) to understand grammatical context
- Named entity recognition: Identifying key entities like people, places or organisations within text.
- Sentiment analysis: Determining the emotional tone behind a series of words to gain an understanding of the attitudes, opinions and emotions expressed.

NLP can be used for customer feedback analysis, translations, summarising large documents, search engines, etc.

Image data

Computer vision enables machines to interpret, analyse and understand visual data.

- Convolutional Neural Networks(CNNs): A specialised class of deep neural networks that can handle grid-like topology data, like images. Good for fast performance in classification and object detection.
- Recurrent Neural Networks(RNNs): Help analyse sequence data, like videos, by remembering context from prior frames. Long Shot-Term Memory(LSTM) networks are commonly used.

Uses

- Facial recognition
- Analyse medical scans
- Self-driving cars

Audio data

Speech recognition, music information retrieval, acoustic modelling, audio compression

- Digital signal processing: converting analogue to digital extracting key features
- Feature extraction: Using techniques like NFCCs and spectrograms to represent audio signals in compact numerical forms.
- Acoustic modelling: ML techniques to teach computers the sounds of speech.
- Voice biometrics
- Speech synthesis: generating artificial human speech using deep learning.

Uses

- Powering Alexa
- Music search like Shazam
- Fraud prevention using voice authorisation
- Hands free

Video data

- Object tracking: SORT and DeepSORT to track items across frames
- Activity detection: recognising patterns of motion and actions in video feeds using neural networks
- Anomaly detection: Identifying abnormal events for surveillance
- Video captioning: Generating natural language descriptions of videos using seq2seq models

Uses

- Improve public safety through surveillance systems
- Analytics in sports for tracking athletic performance, game highlights, computer-assisted coaching

Using distributed processing frameworks

What is Hadoop

Based on Google paper on MapReduce

- Distributed storage
- Distributed processing
- Resilience: If a node fails it can recover. Offers a single view of the data as if it was on a single file system
- Parallel processing. Implements Hadoop MapReduce which can split data into chunks and run the chunks in parallel

Open source tools

- Mapreduce: Processing using different languages
- Hive & Drill: Analytical SQL on aDoop
- Mahout & Spark Mlib: Machine learning
- PIG: Scripting
- Hbase: NoSQL database
- Zookeeper & Ambari: Management and coordination
- Spark: In-memory, data flow engine
- Kafka & Storm: streaming
- Solar & Lucene: Searchign and indexing
- Ooxie: Scheduling
- YARN: Resource management
- Storage: Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS)

Hadoop Distributed File System(HDFS):

Splits large files into smaller blocks and distributes them across multiple nodes in a cluster

Allows for higher fault tolerance and scalability. Each block is replicated across several nodes to ensure data reliability and availability, even with hardware failures.

MapReduce

Divides a task into small sub-tasks that can be executed in parallel across different nodes. Then results are combined.

Yet Another Resource Negotiator(YARN)

Allocates and manages resources like CPU and memory. So multiple applications can use it at the same time

Hadoop Common

Libraries and utilities that support the other Hadoop components.

How Hadoop works

- Data ingestion.
- Data storage - HDFS.
- Data Processing: YARN allocates resources to tasks and run via MApREduce
- Data Retrivel and Analysis: Results can be stored in HDFS. Hive, Pig Hbase can be used to query and analyse the processed data.

Hadoops Distributed File System(HDFS)

- NameNode, master server that manages the filesystem namespace and controls access to files
- DataNodeL the worker nodes that store and retrieve blocks
- Secondary NameNode: Periodically merges the namespace image with the edit log to produce an updated image file. So isn't a backup, but make an image that makes it faster and more efficient since edit log is reduced in size.
- Checkpoint node: Creates checkpoints by merging namespace image with edit log
- Backup Node: Complete backup solution, up to date copy of namespace in memory and on disk, receiving real-time updates from the NameNode.

MapReduce

Map: converts data into tuples(key, value paires)

Reduce: Combines data tuples into a smaller set of tuples.

YARN(Yet another Resource Negotiator)

- ResourceManager(RM) Manages resources and schedules applications
- NodeManageR(NM): Runs on each node and is responsible for managing the node's resources such as CPU, memory and disk
- ApplicationMaster(AM): Application specific entity that negotiates with resourceManager and works with Node manager to execute and monitor tasks.
- Container: A logical unit of computation and resource allocation in YARN. A specific amount of CPU, memory and other

Spark

Apache Spark was developed due to limitations with MapReduce.

Supports interactive queries and streaming. Uses in-memory computing rather than disks.

- Speed. Since it uses in-memory computation, it's much faster. Especially for interactive algorithms.
- Ease of use: Lots of high level API in various languages with a rich set of libraries for SQL, streaming data, machine learning and graph processing.
- Unified engine. Wide range of tasks
- Fault tolerance: Spark ensures fault tolerance through linear -based approach to data recovery.

Spark Architecture

- Resilient distributed datasets(RDDs): Immutable fault-tolerate distributed collections of objects that can be processed in parallel.
- Transformations and actions: Transformations like map and filter create a new RDD. They are lazy and built up a linear map first before running.
- Directed acyclic graph(DAG). Constructs DAG of stages representing the transformations to be executed. The graph is optimised and executed across the cluster.

## Big data architectures

### What is a data lake

Can store structured, semi-structured and unstructured data.

It is a place to store every type of data in its native format with no fixed limits. It auto expands with the accumulated of data.

Cost effective way to accumulate data for future processing.

Low level data is static, transactional data middle, and fast-flowing even-based real-time data is higher level.

![The diagram shows the architecture of a business data lake which is explained in the previous text.](data:image/png;base64,)

Distribution diet takes data from storage tier and converts it to structured data for easier analysis.

Processing tier runs analytical algorithms and user queries with varying real time, interactive and batch to generate structured data for easier analysis

Unified operations tier governs system management and monitoring. It includes auditing, proficiency management, data management, and workflow management.

### Data lake architecture

1. Ingestion layer. Collecting and importing data. Supports multiple data ingestion methods, including match processing, real-time streaming, and API-based data collection.e.g. Apache Kafka, Apache Nifi, AWS Kinesis, Azure Event Hubs.
2. Storage layer. Where raw data is stored. Scalable and cost-effective storage that can handle structured, semi-structured and unstructured data. Distributed file system or object storage systems like Dadoop Distributed File system(HDFS), Amazon S3, Azure Blob Storage, Google Cloud Storage.
3. Processing layer. Transform, cleaning and analysis of data stored in the data lake. Supports a variety of data processing frameworks and tools for batch and real-time processing. e.g. Apache Spark, Aparche Fink, Presto, AWS Glue, Azure Data Factory.
4. Data catalogue and metadata management. Ensures users can find, understand and trust the data in the lake. Comprehensive view of the data including its lineage, quality and usage. e.g. Apache Atlas, AWS Glue Data Catalogue, Azure Data Catalogue.
5. Security and governance layer. Ensures that data in the lake is secure and complies with regulatory requirements. Includes control, encryption, auditing and monitoring to protect sensitive data. e.g. Apache Ranger, SWS Lake Formation, Microsoft Purview.
6.  Consumption layer. Allows users to access and analyse data stored in the lake. Supports varies access methods including, SWL, ML models and data visualisation tools. e.g. Tabeau, Power BI, Jupyter Notebooks.

Key features of a data lake

- Scalability.
- Flexibility. Can store all data types in their native formats. Including structured data from databases, semi-structured data like JSON and SML and unstructured data like text, images, video.
- Cost-effectiveness. Leveraging cloud storage data lakes offer a cost-effective way to store large amounts of data. Pay-as-you-go pricing.
- Accessibility: Multiple data access methods, such as SQL or ML workflows, or big data processing frameworks.
- Integration and interoperability. Works seamlessly with a variety of data processing and analytics tools.
- Data governance and security. Ensure daata security and governance is citical. Access control, encryption and auditing.
- Real--time data processing:

### Risks of data lakes

- Data governance challenges. Without proper governance they can be swamps of used and disorganised data. Robust metadata management, data catalogues and governance frameworks help maintain data quality and compliance.
- Security and privacy concerns. Employing strong encryption, access controls, regular security audits is essential.
- Complexity in data integration. Integrating data could result in issues with data consistency and integrity.
- Use Extract, Transform, Load(ETL) tools and establish clear data integration process.
- Performance issues. Leverage data partitioning, indexing and appropriate data processing frameworks to enhance performance.
- Skill requirements. Invest in training and hiring skilled professions.

### How to build a data lake

1. Define objective and requirements. e.g. improve data analytics, support ML. Identify types of data.
2. Choose the right platform. AWS, Azure, Google Cloud offer scalable and cost-effective solutions. In-prem provide more control but can be more expensive and complex to manage. Select the right storage solution, S3, Blob, etc.
3. Design the architecture. Ingestion layer, storage, processing framework, data catalogue, security.
4. Data ingestion. Data sources, ingestion tools that ingest data in its native format.
5. Data processing and transformation. Clean and prepare data, transform data.
6. Implement data governance. Update and manage metadata so data can be easily discovered and understood. Implement data quality checks and validation. Ensure data lake complies with regulations and standards such as GDPR.
7. Enable data access and analytics. Provide tools such as SWL query engines(e.g. Presto AWS Athena), data visualisation tools(Tableau, Power BI), ML platforms(AWS SageMaker, Azure ML). Train users on how to access and utilise the data lake effectively.
8. Monitor and optimise. Continuously monitor the performance to identify and address bottlenecks. Optimise the data lake's architecture and processes to ensure it remains efficient and cost-effective. e.g. adjusting storage config, refining data ingestion process or upgrading processing frameworks.

### What is a data warehouse?

A data warehouse, is a central repository to store, manage and analyse data. It is structured providing efficient querying and analysis, unlike a data lake.

![The diagram shows the basic architecture of a business data lake which is explained in the previous text.](data:image/png;base64,)

Key features

1. Subject-orientated, so all data relating to a real-world object or event is linked
2. Data from different sources are integrated to provide a single source of truth
3. Data in a SW is non-volatile, real-only and doesn't change.
4. SW are time-variant, allowing for analysis of historical data to show differences over time.

#### Data warehouse schemas

Stored using a star schema. Using primary and foreign keys.

![The diagram shows an example star schema, with a central fact table related to several dimension tables, in which the primary key from each dimension table are foreign keys in the main fact table.](data:image/png;base64,)

Can also have child tables

![The diagram shows the descending hierarchy of a snowflake schema, from the fact table, to dimension tables, to further child dimension tables.](data:image/png;base64,)

### Data cubes

DW use online analytical processing(OLAP) to provide multidimensional analysis of the data. OLAP systems use data cubes to create multidimensional datasets.

### Data vaults

Business keys are separated out and held in entiity-descrete tables called hubs. Attribute data is held in other tables called satellites which are linked to the hubs.

- Hub:: Represents core business entities such as customers, products, orders. Each hub contains a unique list of keys which are stable identifiers for the entities. Also contain metadata.
- Links: Links capture the relationships between hubs. e.g. link between customers and orders. Also contain metadata
- Satellites: Store data the descriptive attributes and contextual information related to hubs and links. Attached to specific hub or link. Allow for tracking changes over time without modifying the core structure of hubs and links.

![A diagram showing a data vault. Business keys are separated out and held in entity-discrete tables, called hubs: Hub_Store, and Hub_Employee. Attribute data is held in other tables called satellites, which are linked to the hubs: Sat_Store, Sat Employment, Sat_Empl_Contact, and Sat_Empl_Details. There is also a link table: Link_Employment.](data:image/png;base64,)

Data volts are better able to accommodate changes and integrate systems. There is no data cleansing.

Principles of a data vault

- Scalable. Handle large volumes of data. Lots of data and new data sources and changes.
- Flexible. Allows integration of disparate data sources.
- Supports agile development.
- Robust audit trail. Since data is traceable to its source.

### Data fabric

The term first emerged in 2013 when Forrester introduced the idea of Information Fabric. You can read about this on the [Forrester website](https://www.forrester.com/blogs/13-08-15-information_fabric_30_delivers_the_next_generation_of_data_virtualization/). Since then, the idea has been further developed. It is not the same as data mesh which you learnt about in the previous unit. Data fabric is focused more on automation. According to Gartner, data fabric is '[a design concept that serves as an integrated layer (fabric) of data and connecting processes](https://www.gartner.com/smarterwithgartner/data-fabric-architecture-is-key-to-modernizing-data-management-and-integration)'

From <[https://app.qa.com/course/big-data-architectures-ai-1698/data-fabric/?context_id=14499&context_resource=lp](https://app.qa.com/course/big-data-architectures-ai-1698/data-fabric/?context_id=14499&context_resource=lp)>

A integration layer over distributed data.

Data virtualisation: Data remains distributed but is integrated as an abstraction layer.

Augmented data catalogue: Provides metadata to provide context.

Knowledge graph: Show relationships between data

Metadata activation: Automated services to help with metadata

Recommendation engine: AI/ML will continuously analyse, learn and make predictions on data integration and the management ecosystem based on the active metadata.

Data preparation and ingestion: Much is automated

Data Ops: Teams work together for continuous integration and delivery.

e.g. Microsoft Fabric has a virtualisation layer. Snowflake AI data cloud, AWS sagemaker
